We need to “build” the fixed‐asset “net” position as of the end date. In our case the changes come only from three groups:
1. The beginning (“initial”) fixed asset balance coming from the “Initial20231231001” row that lists a “Fixed Assets” amount of 5,000,000.00.
2. Additional fixed asset additions (purchases) that are recorded with type “Fixed Assets Purchase.” In our table there are two such rows:
  • One with an amount of 321,724.42 (asset “Processing Equipment4”)
  • A second with an amount of 115,740.01 (asset “Production Line5”)
  Their total is – 
   321,724.42 + 115,740.01 = 437,464.43.
3. Depreciation – which reduces the fixed assets. There is one “Depreciation20240101001” row showing 45,760.13.

Thus, the end value is calculated as

  End Fixed Assets = Initial + Purchases – Depreciation 
    = 5,000,000.00 + 437,464.43 – 45,760.13 
    = 5,437,464.43 – 45,760.13 
    = 5,391,704.30

So the required answer is:
